visual_elements.description: A line drawing showing the front elevation of a single-story house with a wide, covered porch. The porch has a low-pitched gable roof supported by four tapered columns on pedestals, with benches between the columns. The front door is visible on the right side of the porch. This figure is labeled 'A Roofed porch'.

A line drawing showing the front elevation of a two-story house with a prominent, vaulted entryway. The entry has an arched top over double doors and is flanked by windows with shutters. Two dormer windows are on the second story. A vertical dimension line on the right indicates the height from the ground to the peak of the entryway roof, labeled 'Height greater than 12' above grade'. This figure is labeled 'C Vaulted entry way'.

A line drawing showing the front elevation of a house with a small, gabled roof over the entryway. The house has a dormer window above the main windows. A vertical dimension line on the right indicates the height from the ground to the peak of the entry roof, labeled 'Height less than 12' above grade'. This figure is labeled 'B Roofed entry way (not vaulted)'.

A line drawing showing the front elevation of a building with a combination of an arched, colonnaded porch and a taller, vaulted entryway tower. The entryway tower has an arched door. A vertical dimension line on the right indicates the height from the ground to the peak of the entryway tower, labeled 'Height greater than 12' above grade'. This figure is labeled 'D Combination porch & vaulted entry way'.
A gray rectangular box containing white text that serves as a note or cross-reference.
